---
name: backend-respects-csharp-client
description: Backend development rules when a C# biometric application is included as a read-only client
---

# Overview
This rule instructs the AI to treat the included C# biometric application as a read-only reference.
The C# application must NEVER be modified. It exists solely to help the AI understand required API endpoints,
request formats, and expected response structures.

The backend (PHP, JavaScript, MySQL) must adapt to the C# application's existing expectations.

# When to Apply
Apply this rule when:
- A C# biometric or desktop application exists in the repository
- Creating or modifying PHP backend APIs
- Designing database structures that serve the C# application
- Debugging or extending API responses consumed by the C# application

Do NOT apply this rule when:
- Working on unrelated frontend-only features
- Writing documentation or comments only

# Core Principles
- The C# application is READ-ONLY and MUST NOT be changed
- Backend code must adapt to the C# application's requirements
- Existing API endpoints in the C# application take priority over backend preferences

# C# Application Handling Rules
- Never suggest editing, refactoring, or updating the C# application
- Use the C# code only to understand:
  - Required API endpoints
  - Expected request payloads
  - Expected response formats
  - Required fields and data types
- Assume the C# application is already deployed or in use

# API Endpoint Rules
- If the C# application already references an API endpoint:
  - Use the same endpoint path
  - Use the same HTTP method
  - Match the expected response structure exactly
- Before creating new endpoints:
  - Check if an existing endpoint already satisfies the requirement
  - Ask the user for approval before introducing changes

# API Testing & Validation
- Test existing API endpoints first to understand:
  - What data is currently returned
  - What data is missing or incorrect
- Modify backend logic only after confirming endpoint behavior
- Never change API responses in a way that could break the C# client

# Data Responsibility Rules
- Only return the data required by the C# application
- Do not add extra fields unless explicitly requested
- Maintain consistent data types and naming conventions

# Project Structure Rules
- First, understand the current project structure before suggesting changes
- Do NOT restructure folders, layers, or architecture automatically
- If improvements are recommended:
  - Explain the reason clearly
  - Ask the user for approval before applying changes

# General Behavior
- Favor backward compatibility over ideal architecture
- Ask before making structural or architectural decisions
- Prioritize system stability over refactoring
